And elsewhere, Eph. vi. 9, he directs masters to do good to their slaves, forbearing threatening‚ on the same ground, knowing that their Master also is in heaven, who does not regard such differences. In the Clementine Constitutions we have the same. So Clemens Alexandrinus bids us use our slaves as our other selves, since they are men no less than we3 following the saying of the Hebrew wise men. ΙΙΙ. The right of life and death over a slave, then, gives the master a domestic jurisdiction3 which, however, is to be exercised with the same regard to conscience, as a public jurisdiction. So Seneca, as before3 and again, he compares a slave to a subject, and says that, though by a different title, the same things only are lawful in the one case as in the other3 which is especially true with rcgard to this right of taking away life, and what approaches to it.
